PSL190H1-S-20261.courseTitle: Biomedical Research at the Cutting Edge
PSL190H1-S-20261.courseDescription: Explore the thought processes, logic, motivation, techniques, analysis and impact of recent high-profile publications to gain insight into the enterprise of science. Outstanding scientists present recent high-impact papers, and students will examine the research in depth, focusing on the underlying questions, experimental approach, results and significance. Restricted to first-year students. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PSL190H1-S-20261.prerequisite: SBI4U and SCH4U (Grade 12 University Preparation Biology and Chemistry); permission of Department
PSL190H1-S-20261.webTimetableInstructions: Timetable InstructionsThis course has restricted enrollment for newly admitted first-year science degree students with fewer than 4 credits.

PSL201Y1-Y-20259.courseDescription: A survey course covering all organ systems intended for students who are not proceeding further in Physiology.
PSL201Y1-Y-20259.exclusion: Any 300-level PSL course taken previously or concurrently
PSL201Y1-Y-20259.webTimetableInstructions: Timetable InstructionsTerm test will take place Tuesdays in person from 18:00 to 19:00 Toronto time (3 Tuesdays over the course).Delivery InstructionsLectures will be delivered online. Term tests will be timed and will take place in person Tuesdays from 18:00 to 19:00 (Toronto time) on scheduled dates (TBA). Lectures 2h/week and optional synchronous help sessions 1h/week (these will be recorded). The final in-person assessment will be announced by the Faculty of Registrar’s office.

PSL280H1-F-20259.courseTitle: Introduction to Physiologic Adaptations of Marine Mammals
PSL280H1-F-20259.courseDescription: Systems approach to physiology of marine mammals in their aquatic environment. Highlights unique features of cardiovascular, respiratory, renal, urinary, and reproductive systems. Introduces relevant physiology, and makes comparisons to human condition and disease.
PSL280H1-F-20259.prerequisite: (BIO120H1, BIO130H1), CHM136H1/CHM151Y1. Students who do not have all of the required prerequisites are encouraged to contact the course coordinator to seek a waiver.

PSL304H1-F-20259.courseTitle: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology I
PSL304H1-F-20259.courseDescription: Focus on two topics: (1) The regulation of body weight/composition including the hormonal, neural and metabolic interactions between adipose tissue, the brain, the pancreas, and muscle. (2) Cardiovascular and respiratory control systems in adults and neonates in terms of feedback control systems, mechanisms, and clinical disorders.
PSL304H1-F-20259.webTimetableInstructions: Timetable InstructionsThis course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact the undergraduate department at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca

PSL305H1-S-20261.courseTitle: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology II
PSL305H1-S-20261.courseDescription: Focus on two topics: the brain and pregnancy. Delve into the physiology of the central nervous system along with associated diseases as model systems. Learn about fetal and maternal adaptations during pregnancy and the consequences of maladaptation. The course is designed for Physiology Specialist students, although permission is granted to other students upon Departmental approval.
PSL305H1-S-20261.webTimetableInstructions: Timetable InstructionsThis course may be added on your ACORN account during your enrolment start date. The interim status (INT) will be updated to approved (APP) or refused (REF) in August. If you require additional information please contact the undergraduate department at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca

PSL350H1-S-20261.courseDescription: Extend molecular biology concepts to current scientific literature in mammalian physiology. Apply these principles to disease and complex behaviours. Discuss bioethical issues raised by these techniques and their application. Benefit from three weeks in small group seminars lead by research professors focusing on current advances in mammalian molecular biology.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL372H1-F-20259.courseDescription: A laboratory course covering selected topics in physiology. An ancillary fee of $53 will be charged for lab materials.
PSL372H1-F-20259.prerequisite: BIO230H1/(BIO240H1, BIO241H1)/BIO255H1, BCH210H1/BCH242Y1, MAT100-series/PHY100-series, PSL300H1, PSL301H
PSL372H1-F-20259.webTimetableInstructions: Delivery InstructionsWeekly lectures will be delivered online on Thursdays from 12:00-13:00. In-person labs on Fridays for 4h/week @9:00-1:00p.m., synchronous help sessions 1h/week.

PSL374H1-S-20261.courseDescription: A problem-based laboratory course focused on the integration and control of organ systems to understand body functions. Enrollment in this course is restricted to students in the Physiology Specialist and Major Programs although permission is granted to students in other programs upon approval by the Department. An ancillary fee of $53 will be charged for lab materials.
PSL374H1-S-20261.prerequisite: BIO230H1/ (BIO240H1, BIO241H1)/ BIO255H1, PSL300H1, PSL301H1, PSL372H1
PSL374H1-S-20261.webTimetableInstructions: Timetable InstructionsThis course is restricted to two groups of students. Group 1 is given priority access until July 23. PSL399Y1-Y-20259.courseDescription: Credit course for supervised participation in faculty research project. Details at https://www.artsci.utoronto.ca/current/academics/research-opportunities/research-opportunities-program. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.

PSL404H1-F-20259.courseDescription: Regenerative medicine promises to restore body function that has been lost due to disease, damage or age. Students will explore selected molecular, stem cell and tissue engineering developments to better understand how the body normally functions and how cells, tissues, and organs can be repaired or replaced.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL420H1-F-20259.courseDescription: This course provides an in-depth review of the development and function of the male and female reproductive systems. Topics include sex determination and differentiation, steroidogenesis, gametogenesis, hormonal control of the reproductive axis, the female ovulatory cycle, fertilization and implantation, infertility and assisted reproduction approaches. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL420H1/LMP2100H
PSL420H1-F-20259.prerequisite: A minimum grade of 78% is required in PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum grade has not been met students are advised to contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL421H1-S-20261.courseTitle: Pregnancy and Birth: From Implantation to Newborn Life
PSL421H1-S-20261.courseDescription: General overview of the integrated physiological events associated with fetal development, pregnancy and birth. The approach emphasizes physiological processes using insights gained from studies of humans, animals, cells and genes. Where appropriate the clinical consequences of aberrant development are reviewed. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL421H1/PSL1421H
PSL421H1-S-20261.prerequisite: A final grade of 75% or higher in each of PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum is not reached, please contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL425H1-F-20259.courseTitle: Integrative Metabolism and its Endocrine Regulation
PSL425H1-F-20259.courseDescription: This course integrates the newest findings and experimental approaches from cellular and molecular biology into metabolic function at the tissue, organ and whole body level.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL441H1-F-20259.courseTitle: Systems Neuroscience I: Neuroanatomy, Neurophysiology and Higher Cognition
PSL441H1-F-20259.courseDescription: Introduction to systems neuroscience including neuroanatomy, neuroimaging and human neurophysiology (EEG, MEG), neural support for higher cognitive functions (e.g., memory, language), network neuroscience, and computational modeling.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL442H1-S-20261.courseTitle: Systems Neuroscience II: Sensory and Motor
PSL442H1-S-20261.courseDescription: In depth study of the sensory and motor systems, including clinical concerns/applications, neuromodulation, and brain-computer interfaces.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL445H1-F-20259.courseDescription: Overview of the fundamentals of cellular and molecular aspects of brain function. Course material is updated yearly to reflect the rapid evolution of ideas in Neuroscience. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL445H1/PSL1445H/JNR1444Y
PSL445H1-F-20259.prerequisite: PSL300H1, PSL301H1, CJH332H1 or permission of instructor A minimum grade of 78% is required in PSL300H1, PSL301H1 and CJH332H1. If minimum grade has not been met students are advised to contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL446H1-S-20261.courseDescription: Explore topics in neurological disorders and treatments to reinforce and expand your knowledge of cellular and molecular neurophysiology. Course material is updated yearly to reflect the rapid evolution of ideas in this area. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL446H1/PSL1446H/JNR1444Y
PSL446H1-S-20261.prerequisite: PSL300H1, PSL301H1, CJH332H1 or permission of instructor A minimum grade of 78% is required in PSL300H1, PSL301H1 and CJH332H1. If minimum grade has not been met students are advised to contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL450H1-F-20259.courseTitle: Mechanisms of Neural and Endocrinal Secretion
PSL450H1-F-20259.courseDescription: Exocytosis and other aspects of secretion mainly in neurons and neuroendocrine cells, but also in pancreatic cells. Topics include synapse anatomy and physiology, synaptic plasma membrane and vesicle proteins, membrane fusion, genetic tools, endocrine secretion, plasticity in neurotransmitter release, diseases arising from secretion defects.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL452H1-F-20259.courseDescription: Biophysics and molecular biology of ion channels. Topics include equivalent circuits for cells, molecular structure of voltage-gated channels, distribution of channels, relationship between single-channel and whole-cell recording, and regulation of channel function by voltage, phosphorylation, G-proteins and metabolites. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL452H1/PSL1452H
PSL452H1-F-20259.prerequisite: PSL300H1, PSL301H1 A minimum grade of 75% is required in PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum grade has not been met students are advised to contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL462H1-S-20261.courseDescription: Heart anatomy and development, ion channels and contractile proteins involved in cardiac and smooth muscle contraction are studied. Emphasis is on regulation of electrical and contractile function of kinases, metabolism, volume and ions. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL462H1/PSL1462H
PSL462H1-S-20261.prerequisite: PSL300H1, PSL301H1 A minimum grade of 75% is required in PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum grade has not been met students are advised to contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL470H1-S-20261.courseDescription: Development of the cardiovascular system from conception to adulthood with particular emphasis on maturational changes, age-related differences and developmental problems from cellular/molecular to whole organ/system.

enrollmentControls.primaryOrgName: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

PSL472H1-S-20261.courseDescription: This course covers the physiology underlying sleep and circadian rhythms, and their impact on important physiological processes and health. The integrative nature of the basic physiological processes is emphasized via discussions and clinical presentations. Overall, the aim is to present the full spectrum of integrative physiology from molecules and cells to understanding the sick patient.
PSL472H1-S-20261.prerequisite: PSL300H1, PSL301H1 A minimum grade of 75% is required in PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum grade has not been met students are advised to contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.
